.TH REAC-REPACER 8 "2026-06-13" "reac-repacer 0.2.3" "System Manager's Manual"
.SH NAME
reac-repacer \- de-jitter / re-pacing relay for a Roland REAC stream over Wi-Fi
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B reac-repacer
.B \-\-port
.I IN:OUT
.RB [ \-\-port
.IR IN:OUT " ...]"
.RB [ \-\-prefill\-ms
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-servo\-clamp\-ppm
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-pll ]
.RB [ \-\-forward\-only ]
.RB [ \-\-bcast\-only ]
.RB [ \-\-cpu
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-adapt ]
.RB [ \-\-adapt\-min\-ms
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-adapt\-max\-ms
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-adapt\-margin
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-reclaim ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-steady ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-warm\-start ]
.RB [ \-\-lockfile
.IR PATH ]
.br
.B reac-repacer
.RB { \-h | \-\-help }
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B reac-repacer
is a transparent Layer-2 relay that de-jitters a Roland REAC stream
(EtherType 0x8819) carried over a bursty Wi-Fi / WDS path. It sits between the
tunnel side (Wi-Fi, bursty) and the local REAC stagebox and re-emits the master
broadcast at a constant cadence, filling the gaps a clock-slave stagebox cannot
tolerate.
.PP
For each port the daemon buffers the incoming master broadcast for a few
milliseconds and re-emits it on a steady, free-running output clock derived from
the detected sample rate (44.1 / 48 / 96 kHz). Because the stagebox recovers its
word clock from the emit inter-frame interval, the output cadence is held free of
short-term wireless jitter: bursts are absorbed as buffer occupancy swings and
never reach the cadence; occupancy is used only as a slow, sub-ppm trim. The
return direction (stagebox to tunnel) is passed straight through, since the master
owns the clock and tolerates input jitter.
.PP
One daemon handles one or more REAC ports of a single mixer on one shared pacing
clock, so the stageboxes stay sample-phase-aligned with each other. The relay does
not decode REAC, reorder or alter bytes, or do VLAN tagging.
.PP
At least one
.B \-\-port
is required. There is no implicit default: invoked with no port, or with an
unknown flag, the daemon prints usage and exits non-zero rather than launching a
pacer on default interfaces.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-port " IN:OUT"
Define a REAC port as an IN:OUT interface pair (IN = tunnel side, OUT = stagebox
side). Repeat the option once per port. Required.
.TP
.BI \-\-prefill\-ms " N"
Target buffer depth, in milliseconds, filled before emitting begins. Default 12.
.TP
.BI \-\-servo\-clamp\-ppm " N"
Drain-servo clock-bias clamp, in ppm; bounds how fast latency is reclaimed.
Default 700.
.TP
.B \-\-pll
Enable the glacial frequency-lock that converges the base period to null the
long-term occupancy drift. Default off.
.TP
.B \-\-forward\-only
De-jitter only the forward (IN to OUT) direction and do not run the return
pass-through thread. Used on the mixer side. Default off.
.TP
.B \-\-bcast\-only
Accept only the master broadcast frames. Default off.
.TP
.BI \-\-cpu " N"
Core to pin the real-time (SCHED_FIFO) pacing thread to. Default 3.
.TP
.B \-\-adapt
Auto-size the buffer to the observed burst depth. Default off.
.TP
.BI \-\-adapt\-min\-ms " N"
Floor latency, in milliseconds, when shrinking the adaptive window. Default 6.
.TP
.BI \-\-adapt\-max\-ms " N"
Ceiling latency, in milliseconds, when growing the adaptive window. Default 120.
.TP
.BI \-\-adapt\-margin " N"
Keep the occupancy low-water mark this many slots above zero (safety headroom).
Default 20.
.TP
.B \-\-reclaim
Actively shrink latency. This may drop frames and cause clicks; the default
behaviour is grow-only. Default off.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-steady
Disable the steady free-running output clock and restore the per-tick,
servo-paced cadence. The steady clock is on by default.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-warm\-start
Do not persist or restore the converged lock. Warm-start is on by default.
.TP
.BI \-\-lockfile " PATH"
Path of the warm-start state file. Default /etc/reac-repacer.lock.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print the usage message to standard output and exit 0 without starting the
daemon.
.SH STEADY CLOCK AND WARM-START
With the steady free-running output clock (on by default), the emit period
free-runs at the detected base period and is not modulated per tick or per
occupancy swing. Short-term WDS bursts are absorbed as ring-depth swings and never
reach the output cadence, which removes the audible cadence jitter heard on
silences. Occupancy is used only as a glacial trim: the PLL, integrated over
seconds, nudges the base period sub-ppm to null the long-term rate error.
.PP
A glacial lock takes minutes to converge, and a cold start spends those minutes
audibly converging. Warm-start (on by default) persists the converged per-port
emit period to a small state file and, on startup, seeds the base period from it
so the daemon starts already locked. The lock is keyed per output interface, so a
router restores only the periods for the ports it is configured with, and only
when the saved rate label matches the rate detected at startup. A missing or
invalid file is tolerated: the daemon cold-starts exactly as it would without one.
.SH UBUS INTERFACE
When built with libubus support, the daemon registers a
.B reac_repacer
ubus object with two methods.
.TP
.B get
Return a live snapshot: the current target depth, base period, per-port occupancy
and counters, and whether an occupancy retarget walk is in progress.
.IP
.RS
.nf
ubus call reac_repacer get
.fi
.RE
.TP
.B set
Stage a hot retune of the reloadable parameters, applied on the next pacing tick
with no audio dropout. The hot parameters are
.IR prefill_ms ,
.IR adapt_min_ms ,
.IR adapt_max_ms ,
.IR adapt_margin
and
.IR servo_clamp_ppm .
A target-depth change does not flush the ring: the occupancy is walked to the new
depth by a small, bounded clock bias, so audio stays continuous and only the
latency moves.
.IP
.RS
.nf
ubus call reac_repacer set '{"prefill_ms":150}'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Structural parameters (the port / interface mapping and the pinned CPU) are
restart-only: a live change to them over ubus is rejected, not silently ignored.
.SH SIGNALS
.TP
.B SIGHUP
Re-read the hot parameters from the UCI configuration
.RB ( /etc/config/reac-repacer ,
section
.BR main )
and apply them through the same glitch-free path as a ubus
.B set
(omitted options keep their running value). This is how the procd
.B reload
trigger retunes a running daemon.
.TP
.BR SIGINT ", " SIGTERM
Shut the daemon down cleanly.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/reac-repacer.lock
Warm-start state file (overridable with
.BR \-\-lockfile ).
Line-oriented text, one record per output port, with
.RB ` # '
comments and blank lines ignored:
.IP
.RS
.nf
<out_iface> <emit_period_ns> <rate_label_hz> <unix_epoch>
.fi
.RE
.IP
For example:
.IP
.RS
.nf
lan1 124867 96000 1749150000
.fi
.RE
.TP
.I /etc/config/reac-repacer
UCI configuration read at startup and on
.BR SIGHUP .
The
.B main
section holds the global and hot parameters; each
.B port
section is one REAC zone.
.SH EXAMPLES
Three ports of one mixer with a 16 ms target depth:
.PP
.RS
.nf
reac-repacer \-\-port reactap.11:lan1 \-\-port reactap.12:lan2 \\
    \-\-port reactap.13:lan3 \-\-prefill\-ms 16
.fi
.RE
.PP
Mixer-side placement, de-jittering only the forward direction with an adaptive
window:
.PP
.RS
.nf
reac-repacer \-\-port reactap.11:lan1 \-\-forward\-only \-\-adapt
.fi
.RE
.PP
Retune the target depth of a running daemon over ubus, with no dropout:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ubus call reac_repacer set '{"prefill_ms":24}'
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ubus (1),
.BR procd (8)
.SH AUTHOR
Pau Aliagas <linuxnow@gmail.com>
